'''Luchino Visconti di Modrone''', Count of [[Lonate Pozzolo]] ({{IPA-it|luˈkiːno visˈkonti di moˈdroːne|lang}}; 2 November 1906 – 17 March 1976), was an Italian theatre, opera and cinema director, as well as a screenwriter. Visconti was one of the fathers of [[Italian neorealism]] in film, but later moved towards luxurious-looking films obsessed with beauty, death and European history – especially the decay of aristocracy. Among his best-known films are ''[[Ossessione]]'' (1943), ''[[Senso (film)|Senso]]'' (1954), ''[[Rocco and His Brothers]]'' (1960), ''[[The Leopard (1963 film)|The Leopard]]&lt;ref&gt;'THE LEOPARD' IN ITS ORIGINAL LAIR: Care and Authenticity Mark screen Version of Modern Classic
By HERBERT MITGANG. New York Times 29 July 1962: 69&lt;/ref&gt;'' (1963), ''[[The Damned (1969 film)|The Damned]]'' (1969), ''[[Death in Venice (film)|Death in Venice]]'' (1971) and ''[[Ludwig (film)|Ludwig]]'' (1972).
